<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-09-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="341" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                    <head>No. 337.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Jackson</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-09-07"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 7,
                            1886</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 253.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 301, of the 27th
                        ultimo, relative to the case of Francisco Erresures, and have forwarded a
                        copy of Mr. Mariscal’s note of the 26th ultimo, upon the subject, to his
                        excellency John Ireland, governor of Texas, for his information, with the
                        statement that you had called upon Consul Linn at Piedras Negras, for any
                        further facts he may know in the case.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>